{"title_page": "Black pride", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{For|political slogan and US movement |Black Power}}\n{{Black Power sidebar}}\n \n'''Black pride''' is a movement in response to dominant white cultures and ideologies that encourages [[black people]] to celebrate black culture and embrace their African heritage.<ref name=\"Tyson2001\">{{cite book|author=Lois Tyson|title=Learning for a Diverse World: Using Critical Theory to Read and Write about Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNe_wvUh3ewC&pg=PA209|year=2001|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-8153-3774-4|pages=208\u2013209|quote=Because the dominant white culture in America treated African Americans as subalterns rather than full American citizens and full human beings, the Black Pride movement encouraged black Americans to look to Africa for their cultural origins.}}</ref> In the United States, it was a direct response to white [[Racism in the United States|racism]] especially during the [[Civil Rights Movement]].<ref name=\"Glasker2009\">{{cite book|author=Wayne C. Glasker|title=Black Students in the Ivory Tower: African American Student Activism at the University of Pennsylvania, 1967-1990|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=25VDW0nJQ28C&pg=PA28|date=1 June 2009|publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|isbn=1-55849-756-0|page=28|quote=In 1966 the Black Power-black nationalist-black pride movements emerged as equal and opposite reactions to white racism as a reaction of the biracial civil rights movement.}}</ref> Related movements include [[black power]],<ref name=\"Glasker2009\" /> [[black nationalism]],<ref name=\"Glasker2009\" /> [[Black Panthers]] and [[Afrocentrism]]. Black Pride has also been associated with the same racist undertones as White Pride.\n\n==Arts and music==\nBlack pride is a major theme in some works of African American popular musicians. [[Civil Rights Movement]] era songs such as [[The Impressions (American band)|The Impressions]]'s hit songs \"[[We're a Winner]]\"<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2kkcmS0AzMEC&lpg=PA141&ots=5jDPxNG2Bd&dq=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&pg=PA141#v=onepage&q=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&f=false | title=Chicago Soul | publisher=University of Illinois Press | author=Pruter, Robert | year=1991 | location=Champaign, IL | isbn=0-252-06259-0}}</ref> and \"[[Keep On Pushing (song)|Keep on Pushing]]\"<ref name=\"music\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4xCFuu_YadAC&lpg=PA237&ots=M6t6Dmt0pE&dq=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&pg=PA237#v=onepage&q=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&f=false | title=Music Cultures in the United States: An Introduction | publisher=Routledge | author=Koskoff, Ellen | year=2005 | location=New York | isbn=0-415-96589-6}}</ref> and [[James Brown]]'s \"[[Say It Loud \u2013 I'm Black and I'm Proud]]\"<ref name=\"music\" /><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0r7uKMMFBUEC&lpg=PA67&ots=JU2l8ASR1H&dq=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Blues Man: 40 Years with the Blues Legends | publisher=[[AuthorHouse]] | author=Jones, Melvyn \"Deacon\" | year=2008 | location=Bloomington, IN | isbn=978-1-4343-7571-1}}</ref> celebrated black pride. [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s half-time performance at [[Super Bowl 50]], which included homages to [[Malcolm X]] and the [[Black Panthers]], has been described by the media as a display of black pride.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/6873899/beyonce-formation-essay | title=Why Are People Suddenly Afraid of Beyonce's Black Pride? | work=Billboard | date=10 February 2016 | accessdate=11 February 2016 | author=Ex, Kris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2016/0208/Beyonce-s-black-pride-moment-at-the-Super-Bowl | title=Beyonc\u00e9's black pride moment at the Super Bowl | work=The Christian Science Monitor | date=8 February 2016 | accessdate=11 February 2016 | author=Gass, Henry}}</ref>\n\n==Beauty and fashion==\nBeauty standards are a major theme of black pride. Black pride was represented in slogans such as \"[[black is beautiful]]\"<ref name=\"Jha2015\">{{cite book|author=Meeta Jha|title=The Global Beauty Industry: Colorism, Racism, and the National Body|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7fWPCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT46|date=16 September 2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-55795-1|page=46}}</ref><ref name=\"Hurst2015\">{{cite book|editor1=Jos\u00e9 Blanco F.|editor3=Patricia Kay Hunt-Hurst|editor4=Heather Vaughan Lee|editor2=Mary Doering|title=Clothing and Fashion: American Fashion from Head to Toe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hDkVCwAAQBAJ&pg=RA3-PA52|date=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-310-3|page=52}}</ref> which challenged white beauty standards.<ref name=\"Rooks1996\">{{cite book|author=Noliwe M. Rooks|title=Hair Raising: Beauty, Culture, and African American Women|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lCQbqC3lQnEC|year=1996|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0-8135-2312-5}}</ref> Prior to the black pride movement, the majority of black people straightened their hair or wore wigs.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" /> The return to [[natural hair]] styles such as the [[afro]], [[cornrows]], and [[dreadlocks]] were seen as expressions of black pride.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" /><ref name=\"Rooks1996\" /><ref name=\"Craig\">{{cite book|author=Maxine Leeds Craig|title=Ain't I a Beauty Queen? : Black Women, Beauty, and the Politics of Race: Black Women, Beauty, and the Politics of Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6y5SKe325PUC&pg=PA152|date=24 May 2002|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-803255-7}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherrow2006\">{{cite book|author=Victoria Sherrow|title=Encyclopedia of Hair: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Z6vCGbf66YC&pg=PA19|date=January 2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33145-9}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s to 1970s, [[kente cloth]] and the Black Panthers uniform were worn in the U.S. as expressions of black pride.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" /> Headscarves were sometimes worn by [[Nation of Islam]] and other Black Muslim Movement members as an expression of black pride and a symbol of faith.<ref name=\"Craig\" /> Other women used scarves with African prints to cover their hair.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" />\n\n[[Maxine Leeds Craig]] argues that all-black beauty pageants such as [[Miss Black America]] were institutionalized forms of black pride created in response to exclusion from white beauty pageants.<ref name=\"Craig\" />\n\n==International==\n[[file:Mural Malcolm X - Ella Baker - Martin Luther King - Frederick Douglass.jpg|250px|thumb|A mural depicting [[Malcolm X]], [[Ella Baker]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] and [[Frederick Douglass]] in [[Philadelphia]].]]\n\n===Brazil===\nThe black pride movement is very prevalent in [[Brazil]], especially throughout the poorer population, and it is found in the Brazilian [[funk]] music genre that began arose in the late 1960s, as also in [[funk carioca]], that emerged in the late 1980s. Both the origin of Brazilian funk and funk carioca reflects Brazilian black resistance. Ethnomusicologist George Y\u00fadice states that youths were engaging black culture mediated by a U.S. culture industry met with many arguments against their susceptibility to cultural colonization. Although it borrows some ingredients from [[hip hop]], its style still remains unique to Brazil (mainly Rio de Janeiro and also S\u00e3o Paulo).<ref>{{Harvnb|Y\u00fadice|1994}}</ref>\n\n===Jamaica===\nBlack pride has been a central theme of the originally [[Jamaica]]n [[Rastafari movement]] since the second half of the 20th century. It has been described as \"a rock in the face of expressions of white superiority.\"<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/rastafari/history/slavery.shtml Rastafari and slavery]</ref>\n\n===United States===\nThe slogan has been used in the [[United States]] by [[African Americans]] to celebrate heritage<ref name=\"Tyson2001\" /> and personal pride. The black pride movement is closely linked with the developments of the [[civil rights movement]] and [[Black Power movement]]<ref name=\"Glasker2009\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vahistorical.org/collections-and-resources/virginia-history-explorer/civil-rights-movement-virginia/rising-black |title=Rising Black Consciousness |publisher=[[Virginia Historical Society]] |quote=As the civil rights movement gained ground, removing the stigma of inferiority not only in schools but throughout society, black pride increased. |accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> which opposed the conditions of the United States' segregated society, and lobbied for better treatment for people of all races.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Black Arts Movement]]\n*[[Black genocide conspiracy theory]]\n*[[Afrocentrism]]\n*[[Africarium]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|last= Y\u00fadice |first= George |author-link= George Y\u00fadice |chapter= The Funkification of Rio |title= Microphone Fiends: Youth Music and Youth Culture |editor1-last= Ross |editor1-first= Andrew |editor2-first= Tricia |editor2-last= Rose |pages= 193\u2013220 |place= London |publisher= Routledge |year= 1994 |isbn= 978-0-415-90907-5 }}\n\n{{African American topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black Pride}}\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:Black Power]]\n[[Category:Identity politics]]\n[[Category:Politics and race]]\n[[Category:Pride]]\n[[Category:Racism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{For|political slogan and US movement |Black Power}}\n{{Black Power sidebar}}\n \n'''Black pride''' is a movement in response to dominant white cultures and ideologies that encourages [[black people]] to celebrate black culture and embrace their African heritage.<ref name=\"Tyson2001\">{{cite book|author=Lois Tyson|title=Learning for a Diverse World: Using Critical Theory to Read and Write about Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNe_wvUh3ewC&pg=PA209|year=2001|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-8153-3774-4|pages=208\u2013209|quote=Because the dominant white culture in America treated African Americans as subalterns rather than full American citizens and full human beings, the Black Pride movement encouraged black Americans to look to Africa for their cultural origins.}}</ref> In the United States, it was a direct response to white [[Racism in the United States|racism]] especially during the [[Civil Rights Movement]].<ref name=\"Glasker2009\">{{cite book|author=Wayne C. Glasker|title=Black Students in the Ivory Tower: African American Student Activism at the University of Pennsylvania, 1967-1990|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=25VDW0nJQ28C&pg=PA28|date=1 June 2009|publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|isbn=1-55849-756-0|page=28|quote=In 1966 the Black Power-black nationalist-black pride movements emerged as equal and opposite reactions to white racism as a reaction of the biracial civil rights movement.}}</ref> Related movements include [[black power]],<ref name=\"Glasker2009\" /> [[black nationalism]],<ref name=\"Glasker2009\" /> [[Black Panthers]] and [[Afrocentrism]].\n\n==Arts and music==\nBlack pride is a major theme in some works of African American popular musicians. [[Civil Rights Movement]] era songs such as [[The Impressions (American band)|The Impressions]]'s hit songs \"[[We're a Winner]]\"<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2kkcmS0AzMEC&lpg=PA141&ots=5jDPxNG2Bd&dq=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&pg=PA141#v=onepage&q=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&f=false | title=Chicago Soul | publisher=University of Illinois Press | author=Pruter, Robert | year=1991 | location=Champaign, IL | isbn=0-252-06259-0}}</ref> and \"[[Keep On Pushing (song)|Keep on Pushing]]\"<ref name=\"music\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4xCFuu_YadAC&lpg=PA237&ots=M6t6Dmt0pE&dq=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&pg=PA237#v=onepage&q=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&f=false | title=Music Cultures in the United States: An Introduction | publisher=Routledge | author=Koskoff, Ellen | year=2005 | location=New York | isbn=0-415-96589-6}}</ref> and [[James Brown]]'s \"[[Say It Loud \u2013 I'm Black and I'm Proud]]\"<ref name=\"music\" /><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0r7uKMMFBUEC&lpg=PA67&ots=JU2l8ASR1H&dq=We're%20a%20Winner%20black%20pride&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Blues Man: 40 Years with the Blues Legends | publisher=[[AuthorHouse]] | author=Jones, Melvyn \"Deacon\" | year=2008 | location=Bloomington, IN | isbn=978-1-4343-7571-1}}</ref> celebrated black pride. [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s half-time performance at [[Super Bowl 50]], which included homages to [[Malcolm X]] and the [[Black Panthers]], has been described by the media as a display of black pride.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/6873899/beyonce-formation-essay | title=Why Are People Suddenly Afraid of Beyonce's Black Pride? | work=Billboard | date=10 February 2016 | accessdate=11 February 2016 | author=Ex, Kris}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2016/0208/Beyonce-s-black-pride-moment-at-the-Super-Bowl | title=Beyonc\u00e9's black pride moment at the Super Bowl | work=The Christian Science Monitor | date=8 February 2016 | accessdate=11 February 2016 | author=Gass, Henry}}</ref>\n\n==Beauty and fashion==\nBeauty standards are a major theme of black pride. Black pride was represented in slogans such as \"[[black is beautiful]]\"<ref name=\"Jha2015\">{{cite book|author=Meeta Jha|title=The Global Beauty Industry: Colorism, Racism, and the National Body|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7fWPCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT46|date=16 September 2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-55795-1|page=46}}</ref><ref name=\"Hurst2015\">{{cite book|editor1=Jos\u00e9 Blanco F.|editor3=Patricia Kay Hunt-Hurst|editor4=Heather Vaughan Lee|editor2=Mary Doering|title=Clothing and Fashion: American Fashion from Head to Toe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hDkVCwAAQBAJ&pg=RA3-PA52|date=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-310-3|page=52}}</ref> which challenged white beauty standards.<ref name=\"Rooks1996\">{{cite book|author=Noliwe M. Rooks|title=Hair Raising: Beauty, Culture, and African American Women|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lCQbqC3lQnEC|year=1996|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0-8135-2312-5}}</ref> Prior to the black pride movement, the majority of black people straightened their hair or wore wigs.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" /> The return to [[natural hair]] styles such as the [[afro]], [[cornrows]], and [[dreadlocks]] were seen as expressions of black pride.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" /><ref name=\"Rooks1996\" /><ref name=\"Craig\">{{cite book|author=Maxine Leeds Craig|title=Ain't I a Beauty Queen? : Black Women, Beauty, and the Politics of Race: Black Women, Beauty, and the Politics of Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6y5SKe325PUC&pg=PA152|date=24 May 2002|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-803255-7}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherrow2006\">{{cite book|author=Victoria Sherrow|title=Encyclopedia of Hair: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Z6vCGbf66YC&pg=PA19|date=January 2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33145-9}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s to 1970s, [[kente cloth]] and the Black Panthers uniform were worn in the U.S. as expressions of black pride.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" /> Headscarves were sometimes worn by [[Nation of Islam]] and other Black Muslim Movement members as an expression of black pride and a symbol of faith.<ref name=\"Craig\" /> Other women used scarves with African prints to cover their hair.<ref name=\"Hurst2015\" />\n\n[[Maxine Leeds Craig]] argues that all-black beauty pageants such as [[Miss Black America]] were institutionalized forms of black pride created in response to exclusion from white beauty pageants.<ref name=\"Craig\" />\n\n==International==\n[[file:Mural Malcolm X - Ella Baker - Martin Luther King - Frederick Douglass.jpg|250px|thumb|A mural depicting [[Malcolm X]], [[Ella Baker]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] and [[Frederick Douglass]] in [[Philadelphia]].]]\n\n===Brazil===\nThe black pride movement is very prevalent in [[Brazil]], especially throughout the poorer population, and it is found in the Brazilian [[funk]] music genre that began arose in the late 1960s, as also in [[funk carioca]], that emerged in the late 1980s. Both the origin of Brazilian funk and funk carioca reflects Brazilian black resistance. Ethnomusicologist George Y\u00fadice states that youths were engaging black culture mediated by a U.S. culture industry met with many arguments against their susceptibility to cultural colonization. Although it borrows some ingredients from [[hip hop]], its style still remains unique to Brazil (mainly Rio de Janeiro and also S\u00e3o Paulo).<ref>{{Harvnb|Y\u00fadice|1994}}</ref>\n\n===Jamaica===\nBlack pride has been a central theme of the originally [[Jamaica]]n [[Rastafari movement]] since the second half of the 20th century. It has been described as \"a rock in the face of expressions of white superiority.\"<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/rastafari/history/slavery.shtml Rastafari and slavery]</ref>\n\n===United States===\nThe slogan has been used in the [[United States]] by [[African Americans]] to celebrate heritage<ref name=\"Tyson2001\" /> and personal pride. The black pride movement is closely linked with the developments of the [[civil rights movement]] and [[Black Power movement]]<ref name=\"Glasker2009\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vahistorical.org/collections-and-resources/virginia-history-explorer/civil-rights-movement-virginia/rising-black |title=Rising Black Consciousness |publisher=[[Virginia Historical Society]] |quote=As the civil rights movement gained ground, removing the stigma of inferiority not only in schools but throughout society, black pride increased. |accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> which opposed the conditions of the United States' segregated society, and lobbied for better treatment for people of all races.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Black Arts Movement]]\n*[[Black genocide conspiracy theory]]\n*[[Afrocentrism]]\n*[[Africarium]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|last= Y\u00fadice |first= George |author-link= George Y\u00fadice |chapter= The Funkification of Rio |title= Microphone Fiends: Youth Music and Youth Culture |editor1-last= Ross |editor1-first= Andrew |editor2-first= Tricia |editor2-last= Rose |pages= 193\u2013220 |place= London |publisher= Routledge |year= 1994 |isbn= 978-0-415-90907-5 }}\n\n{{African American topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black Pride}}\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:Black Power]]\n[[Category:Identity politics]]\n[[Category:Politics and race]]\n[[Category:Pride]]\n[[Category:Racism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "2405:6e00:2e45:8601:45d7:fe16:a4f2:629a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_pride"}
